May the weekend find you breathing in the scent of the forests, splashing in water, climbing a cliff or watching an owl. Wherever you may be please keep in mind that we share outdoor spaces with other people, wildlife and plants. Be mindful of others.

Thanks @katieboue for the motivation!

#respect
#😌be good 🙏🏼 be kind 😊 be happy

@noapproachnate is a climber from Columbus, OH. The language of belay (full trust in your partner), send (goal orientation) and “I’ve got you” (the bond that connects) translates to the social equity movement we are experiencing and participating in. 
His post about why we need to speak up and make space in our social media conversations for this movement resonated. Hopefully you’ll take five minutes to listen to his voice, consider your action (or lack of) and become part of how we realign the United States by eliminating systemic racism. 
If you are white and reading this consider your actions. Is this moment in time making you feel guilt  and shame? Are you defensive and rationalizing your avoidance of action because you have prioritized your emotions over those that are suffering? 
Take action today. Sign a petition, contact your elected officials, be open to conversation, start conversations, understand white privilege and amplify your voice. Nate and millions of others are counting on us.

@bgcmarketplace :: Talent is in every person. When we find the one activity that brings us happiness,  our talent shines.

From @browngirlsclimb : 
Navigating the ‘outdoor industry’ brands is a challenge and we know that limited resources exist to find the products and companies that fit your values and needs. 

Currently, there is limited data on the number of Black and Brown, Women, and Queer entrepreneurs in the outdoor industry. This lack of representation doesn’t match the changing demographic of outdoor recreationalists and the general population in this country. The multicultural shopper holds trillions in spending potential and we know, together, we have the power to change the way our money is invested.

Additionally, within large companies to small, finding products that fit our bodies and our values is a growing challenge for everyone wanting to experience their version of the ‘outdoors’. Corporate responsibility initiatives and inclusive product development should be celebrated not hidden in hours worth of online searches. @browngirlsclimb(BGC) believes everyone should have access to information to guide their purchases, that’s why they created the @bgcmarketplace. 

The BGC Marketplace is a values based shopping experience for the outdoor lover, committed to a better future for all. This platform allows you to search the gear you need while supporting the causes you care about.

Created by the folks at Brown Girls Climb, a BIPOC women led collective and social enterprise, this tool is designed for us to navigate capitalism the best we can while investing in companies that are investing in us.

We/I welcome you to join this new initiative and the efforts of Brown Girls Climb, by supporting their @ifundwomen crowdfunding campaign. Find the link in our bio or at @browngirlsclimb

Each of us can change the way business is typically run. We/I believe that the BGC Marketplace is just one step towards the transformative change we hope to see in the future. 
••••••••••••••••
Please consider supporting the marketplace.

node.text:
"Only the mediocre are always at their best." Quote by French writer Jean Giraudoux.

Knowing that our energy, physical and intellectual, ebbs and flows like the tides is nice place to start. Not every day is the special "summit moment" and nor should they be. We would burn out from the intensity. 

When we take time aside, not reacting to what society foists upon us, we have a chance to recharge. We are ready to create the moments that define our lives. 

Standing on a beach as wavelets sand one's toes, sitting under a tree listening to birds sing or laying on a rock in the middle the night watching the stars are small ways in which we can "defrag the hard-drive". Perhaps these simple, humble moments, where we can reflect upon the immensity of life, are sources of energy.

node.text:
Galen Rowell, Rick Ridgeway and Jimmy Chin pulling carts along the shore of a hyper-saline lake in the Chang Tang Region of Tibet. 19 years ago we set out to observe and document the calving grounds of the chiru, an ungulate of the Capridea genus. 

In 2002 we set out for a seven week traverse of the Chang Tang Plateau with the support of the National Geographic Society. Working on the foundation of George Schaller we located the calving grounds. The area is now protected, hopefully offering a better existence for these threatened animals.

We rationed food, drank murky water of questionable provenance, slept in the shadow of an old wolf that started following us, walked in circle during a snow storm and retold our favorite stories every other night. This was Galen's last expedition. The care that Galen and Rick shared with Jimmy, mentoring him as photographer and film maker, is to this day the standard that I aspire to when helping others.

node.text:
@jessroskelley and his dog Mugs.

After Jess lost his life on Howse Peak, Canada in 2019 his family and close friends created the @jessroskelleyfoundation to honor their son, sibling and friend.

The first project was to build a climbing boulder @riverfrontspokane in conjunction with @spokaneparks. On the 21st of May 2021 the park was opened to the public. 

In addition to basketball courts, a skate park, a climbing boulder, a tower with three slides, a slack line and picnic pavilions the park has an interpretive center based on the  Ice Age Floods that occurred 13-15,000 years ago when glacial Lake Missoula drained. The park is named after this event, one that has a lasting imprint on Eastern Washington.

@jbroskelley @roskelleyjohn @jordanroskelley @alliroskelley hosted the grand opening under warm blue skies.

Thanks to Land Water Water Conservation Fund @lwcfcoalition,
@spokaneparks, individual sponsors and @thenorthface for getting this project over the finish line.

If you are in Spokane check out the boulder. If you are driving through it's a better break from the hum of Interstate 90 than a bag of chips.

"Fortitude Vincimus"  by endurance we conquer -Ernest Shackleton

#publiclands #spokane #riverfront #skatepark #climb 

On the traditional lands of the Spokane, Salish and related peoples.

node.text:
The @unitednations is observing May 20th as World Bee Day.  From the UN webpage: 
----
We all depend on the survival of bees.
Bees and other pollinators, such as butterflies, bats and hummingbirds, are increasingly under threat from human activities.
Pollination is, however, a fundamental process for the survival of our ecosystems. Nearly 90% of the world’s wild flowering plant species depend, entirely, or at least in part, on animal pollination, along with more than 75% of the world’s food crops and 35% of global agricultural land. Not only do pollinators contribute directly to food security, but they are key to conserving biodiversity.
To raise awareness of the importance of pollinators, the threats they face and their contribution to sustainable development, the UN designated 20 May as World Bee Day.
The goal is to strengthen measures aimed at protecting bees and other pollinators, which would significantly contribute to solving problems related to the global food supply and eliminate hunger in developing countries.
We all depend on pollinators and it is, therefore, crucial to monitor their decline and halt the loss of biodiversity.

----

As an amateur bee keeper it's wonderful to see the importance of pollinators and how their well being is connected to human well being. These humble insects keep humans fed. 

Thanks bees!

One hundred years ago on the 19th of May the Mount Everest Reconnaissance Expedition began the trek from Darjeeling, India to base of Mt Everest via the Tibetan Plateau.  The English, under the guidance and support of the Royal Geographic Society  @rgs_ibg set out to climb "The Third Pole". 

In 1921 they started a bit late, not grasping the full effect of the monsoon. The effort of 1921 was not for naught as the team was able to unlock the passage of the east fork of the Rongbuk Glacier.  The team reassembled in 1922, again getting doused by the monsoon and tragically having seven of the climbing Sherpa killed in an avalanche. The team returned earlier in 1924 with monsoon knowhow and improved oxygen apparatuses. 

George Leigh Mallory was a member of all three expeditions and lost his life on the 8th of June 1924 along with his climbing partner Sandy Irvine.  While we will never know exactly what transpired on that fateful day, we have an appreciation for what they tried to do. Their effort was the basis for subsequent generations of climbers that eventually climbed Chomolungma, Mother Goddess of the Snows. 

In 2019 my friends @m_synnott  @thom.dharma.pollard & @renan_ozturk climbed the route that was pioneered by Mallory in the 20s. With support from @natgeo they shared their story via the magazine and a documentary.  Their work sheds light, through the lens of modern exploration, of what the pioneering climbers encountered. Layer up the pressure this mountain receives from today's climber and it is obvious how the past-time we so enjoy has changed - from the landscape to the participants - over the past century. 

Mark's book, "The Third Pole" digs deep into these changes from the vantage of a seasoned alpinist. If mountaineering is your passion,  Mark's book is worthy of your collection. If you are new to this arcane yet deadly sport, you'll understand the draw people have and how the vicissitude of altitude plays for keeps.

The opening image is courtesy of Howard Somervell and was taken in 1922 along the same route used in 1921. The remainder are by Renan.

Time is relative. We don’t remember everything equally well. The moments that etch into our beings are the ones where something changes.

As climbers we hope that it’s the summit moment; clouds parting, a ray of sunshine beaming down and touching our foreheads as we embrace our teammates in joy. Climbing is an inherently frivolous, dangerous, and selfish pursuit – if you spend a life in the mountains and are still able to read this, you understand and accept the value set of putting yourself at risk – and we do it all for a few exultant minutes at the top.

But the moments we remember aren’t always so happy. The reality is that people die in the mountains. And sometimes the moments of death – or near death – are the ones that stay with us.

I’ve had several of these moments. Instants where things have gone very wrong, and there’s no way to turn back the clock.
----------------
Please, if you have finished your chores, consider reading an essay  @hodinkee about 
"The Recycler". 

First image by ST Shaw. We skied into the Kichatna Spires in 1991.
Second image of Anselme Baud @baudanselme on the first ski descent of the Western Ice Steam, Mt Vinson, Antarctica 1997.

Photo by Conrad Anker on May 17, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Prior to 2016, my conversations with the recycler were shouting matches. The situation went afoul in a matter of seconds and it seemed my life was done. Within the same amount of time I would be through the trial and still breathing. The recycler would shout for my life and I'd yell back louder. "NOT TODAY!!" I'd walk away feeling a bit stronger, having stared down death. Yet on the 16th of November 2016, the recycler wanted a longer slower conversation.'.

Photo shared by Conrad Anker on May 17, 2021 tagging @hodinkee. May be an image of text that says 'is now over. You have nothing to prove to yourself. Let it go. I'm learning how to do that. Yet at the same time, I long for the intensity of looking over a crest of jagged peaks, whipped by wind and bitten by the cold as I re-rack for the next pitch. I'm always tempted to risk everything for another moment of glory, even if know that, at best, it'll last a matter of minutes.'.

I'm so excited to join my friends @themuseumofmodernart in launching the #MoMAPhotoClub. Get inspired by the amateur photography clubs in their new exhibition, “Fotoclubismo: Brazilian Modernist Photography, 1946–1964.” Each month this summer, we’re encouraging everyone to get outside and get creative with a new photo challenge.

Everyone is invited to join the MoMA Photo Club, no experience necessary! Here’s how to participate: 

—Grab a camera — your phone works — head outside and get creative (bring a friend!)
—Share your photos on social media with the hashtag #MoMAPhotoClub and tag @themuseumofmodernart 
—Along with MoMA, we’ll be resharing some of our favorite shots.

To kick things off in May, I'm inviting you to share your own interpretations of the theme Abstractions from Nature. Take a closer look at the world around you. How can you photograph something familiar in nature from a new perspective? Try zooming in; make it hard to guess what it is you’re capturing. Notice textures, search for new shapes, and play with angles.
 
We can’t wait to see and share what you create!
